    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1966-02-04T15:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1966-02-04T15:00:00-05:00" n="290"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d290">
                <head>290. Memorandum From the President’s Deputy Special Assistant for National
                    Security Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_KRW1" type="from">Komer</persName>) to
                    President <persName type="to">Johnson</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d290fn1">Source: Johnson Library, National
                        Security File, Memos to the President, <persName corresp="#p_BMG1">McGeorge
                            Bundy</persName>, Vol. 19, Jan. 19–Feb. 4, 1966. Confidential. A
                        handwritten note on the memorandum reads, “Rec’d 4:30 p.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1966-02-04T15:00:00-05:00">February 4, 1966, 3 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="italic">Pakistan too</hi>. If we announce another India <gloss
                        target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> 480 allotment, State and <gloss target="#t_AID1"
                        >AID</gloss> urge that we at least make a private gesture toward Pakistan
                    too. <gloss target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss> needs are far less than those of India,
                    but Ayub is under fire <pb facs="0599" n="561" xml:id="pg_561"/> and has to show
                    that we aren’t neglecting Pakistan after he came here.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d290fn2">In a February 5 telephone conversation with Vice President
                            <persName corresp="#p_HHH1">Humphrey</persName>, President <persName
                            corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName> noted that Ayub had run a political
                        risk in taking the stand he did at Tashkent. <persName corresp="#p_JLB1"
                            >Johnson</persName> felt that Ayub had reached an accommodation with
                        India in good part in order to maintain his credibility with the United
                        States. <persName corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName> consequently felt
                        that the United States should do what it could to help Ayub weather the
                        political storm. (Johnson Library, Recordings and Transcripts, Recording of
                        Telephone Conversation Between President <persName corresp="#p_JLB1"
                            >Johnson</persName> and Vice President <persName corresp="#p_HHH1"
                            >Humphrey</persName>, February 5, 1966, 10:15 a.m., Tape F66.04, Side B,
                        PNO 1 40)</note> The minimum sensible (which would require no publicity)
                    would be to tell the Paks we will shortly begin talks for a new interim <gloss
                        target="#t_PL1">PL</gloss> 480 deal to cover their needs through spring
                    (perhaps 200,000 tons of grain and 25,000 tons of oil). We could also invite the
                        <gloss target="#t_Pak1">Pak</gloss> Agriculture Minister (a friend) to come
                    here next month, to match the <persName corresp="#p_SC1">Subramaniam</persName>
                    visit.</p>
                <p>This step commits us to little, while covering our <gloss target="#t_Pak1"
                        >Pak</gloss> flank. We could spin out negotiations and terms as much as
                    needed. Here is yet another “gimme”, but I can’t avoid making these pleas. I’m
                    unfortunately the staffer responsible to you for half the beggars in the
                    world.</p>
                <p rend="flushleft">Approve<note n="3" xml:id="d290fn3">President <persName
                            corresp="#p_JLB1">Johnson</persName> checked this option.</note>
                </p>
                <p rend="flushleft">Hold up</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KRW1">
                            <hi rend="strong">R.W. Komer</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
